Because not that much we renamed, you can also use the layout of the legacy web pages from
$PLANROOT/ObjectiveTree/10-refactor-documentation/03-define-information-architecture/02-reference-manual-chapter-map/01-define-the-group-and-page-structure/01-establish-legacy-group-and-page-structure/legacy-overview.md for strong hints.

Make a table just like that for the tags shown above:
```
| TAG | INPUT | OUTPUT | TITLE |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| `book_writing_intro` | `writing_intro.md` | `book_writing_intro.html` | Writing Debug Output: Introduction |
| `chapter_attach_gdb` | `attach_gdb.md` | `chapter_attach_gdb.html` | Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program |
...
```

The two already shown are trivial, but I found them as follows (I did NOT assume you could just convert the tag into the md name and html file):

1) I did grep `book_writing_intro` in all *.md files and found:
```
chapter-writing-debug-output.md:- @subpage book_writing_intro
reference-manual-writing-debug-output.md:- @subpage book_writing_intro
writing_intro.md:@page book_writing_intro Writing Debug Output: Introduction
```
in that case it is clear that the `@page` is responsible for creating the html page; hence `writing_intro.md` is the INPUT file.
This also gives us the title. I then did grep that title in all html files in $BUILDDIR/doc to find:
```
book_writing_intro.html:8:  <title>libcwd: Writing Debug Output: Introduction</title>
book_writing_intro.html:100:  <div class="headertitle"><div class="title">Writing Debug Output: Introduction </div></div>
pages.html:113:<tr id="row_1_1_0_" class="even"><td class="entry"><span style="width:48px;display:inline-block;">&#160;</span><a class="el" href="book_writing_intro.html" target="_self">Writing Debug Output: Introduction</a></td><td class="desc"></td></tr>
reference-manual-writing-debug-output.html:105:<li><a class="el" href="book_writing_intro.html" title="Writing Debug Output: Introduction">Writing Debug Output: Introduction</a></li>
```
from which it is clear that the content ended up in `book_writing_intro.html`.

2) Same for `chapter_attach_gdb`:
```
doc>grep -Hn chapter_attach_gdb *.md
attach_gdb.md:1:@page chapter_attach_gdb Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program
chapter-runtime.md:7:- @subpage chapter_attach_gdb
rcfile.md:5:In order to use <code>\link chapter_attach_gdb attach_gdb() \endlink</code> and/or to read debug channel states
reference-manual-runtime.md:7:- @subpage chapter_attach_gdb
```
Thus INPUT = attach_gdb.md, TITLE = Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program, and
```
build/doc>grep -Hn 'Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program' *.html
chapter_attach_gdb.html:8:  <title>libcwd: Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program</title>
chapter_attach_gdb.html:100:  <div class="headertitle"><div class="title">Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program </div></div>
pages.html:131:<tr id="row_1_3_1_" class="even"><td class="entry"><span style="width:48px;display:inline-block;">&#160;</span><a class="el" href="chapter_attach_gdb.html" target="_self">Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program</a></td><td class="desc"></td></tr>
reference-manual-runtime.html:106:<li><a class="el" href="chapter_attach_gdb.html" title="Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program">Starting A gdb Session From A Running Program</a></li>
```
Thus OUTPUT = chapter_attach_gdb.html


Write the result to $PLANROOT/current_objective/overview.md

